## Severity
Minor
## Dimension
kiss
## Location
src/rules.rs:295-310 (extract_extensions_from_tool_input, Glob branch)
## Violation
```rust
"Glob" => {
    if let Some(pattern) = input.get("pattern").and_then(|v| v.as_str()) {
        if let Some(ext_part) = pattern.rsplit('.').next() {
            let ext = ext_part.trim_end_matches(&['*', '?', ']', ')'][..]);
            if !ext.is_empty() && ext.len() < 10 {
                extensions.push(ext.to_string());
            }
        }
    }
}
```

`rsplit('.').next()` for a pattern like `*.tar.gz` returns `"gz"` — fine — but for `src/util` returns the entire string, treating `util` as an extension. The 10-character cutoff catches some of these false positives but not others (e.g. `foo`). The trim list `&['*', '?', ']', ')']` is incomplete: braces (`{html,htm}`) are not handled, so `*.{rs,toml}` returns `"toml}"` minus nothing. The whole branch is a regex masquerading as imperative code.
## Mandated refactor
Use a single compiled regex `\.([A-Za-z0-9]{1,8})(?:[\*\?\]\}\)]*)?$` (compiled once via `OnceLock<Regex>`), capture group 1 = extension. Reject patterns with no embedded `.`. Add tests for `*.tar.gz`, `*.{rs,toml}`, `src/util`, `**/*.rs`, and `*`.
